ashire, Northumberland, Shropshire, Staffordshire), or Haughton le Skerne (Durham). The placenames derive from Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Houghton  .","Irish: adopted for <b>Ó hEacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eachán</i>’, a pet form of the personal name <i>Eachaidh</i> (see   Hoey  ).","Irish: adopted for <b>Ó hEachtair</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eachtair</i>’, a personal name of uncertain origin. Compare   Hoctor  ."]},{"name":"Howton","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Houghton  ."]},{"name":"Hufton","meanings":["English: habitational name; probably from Stony Houghton in Pleasley (Derbyshire), the name of which derives from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Houghton  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":30,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Houghton was born about 1260, in England as the son of John Houghton. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in 1313, at the age of 54."},"et":{"about 1260–1313":"umbes 1260–1313","1260–1313":"1260–1313","1284–1357":"1284–1357","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1313":"1313","1357":"1357","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 126